WEBVTT

00:13.567 --> 00:14.733
GLENN VILLENEUVE:
I like to come up here

00:14.800 --> 00:16.600
and look around
at this time of year.

00:17.567 --> 00:20.500
Gives me a good view,
gets me up
above some of the trees,

00:20.600 --> 00:21.700
I can see further.

00:23.233 --> 00:26.667
Up in these mountains
several miles from camp,
there are Dall sheep.

00:26.733 --> 00:28.400
And in a couple of months
from now,

00:28.467 --> 00:30.033
I'll be hunting those sheep.

00:31.433 --> 00:33.467
There's a lot of
country up there,

00:33.533 --> 00:35.700
and the sheep are spread out,
all over it.

00:36.000 --> 00:37.767
So what I need to do
at this time of year,

00:37.833 --> 00:39.500
in preparation to hunt
for 'em,

00:39.567 --> 00:40.900
is to go out
and scout for them.

00:43.100 --> 00:44.933
I'm not looking
for just any sheep,

00:45.000 --> 00:47.433
the ewes, the young rams,
the lambs,

00:47.533 --> 00:51.033
those are left,
to reproduce to maintain
the population.

00:51.100 --> 00:53.233
I'm looking for a big ram
like this one.

00:53.300 --> 00:55.433
This is the last sheep
I killed in these mountains.

00:55.500 --> 00:56.933
But to find a big sheep
like this

00:57.000 --> 00:58.267
is a real challenge.

01:06.267 --> 01:09.300
Whenever I go out
this time of year,
I always carry my rifle.

01:10.567 --> 01:12.333
Without a rifle,
I'd be defenceless,

01:12.400 --> 01:13.700
and there are bears
around here.

01:16.333 --> 01:18.333
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

01:41.000 --> 01:42.233
NARRATOR:
For Glenn Villeneuve,

01:42.300 --> 01:44.633
scouting animal behaviour
in the Brooks Range

01:44.700 --> 01:47.367
is key to harvesting meat
and protein for survival.

01:48.100 --> 01:51.233
In the fall,
Dall sheep hunting season
will be open,

01:51.300 --> 01:53.700
and locating them
now is a priority.

01:54.600 --> 01:56.433
VILLENEUVE: I'm gonna head up
into the mountains
this morning,

01:56.500 --> 01:58.033
spend a few days
walking around,

01:59.033 --> 02:01.500
finding a promising area
to hunt a couple of months
from now.

02:02.967 --> 02:05.800
Hunting sheep is the most
physically demanding hunting
I do.

02:05.867 --> 02:07.133
I have to walk further,

02:08.533 --> 02:10.300
in more difficult terrain,

02:10.367 --> 02:13.100
and spend more time
seeking out sheep
than any other animal I hunt.

02:16.200 --> 02:17.867
Sheep like to stay up high,

02:18.033 --> 02:20.333
where there are rocks
they can escape to when
the predators are around,

02:20.433 --> 02:21.567
that's how they get away
from wolves,

02:21.633 --> 02:22.833
that's how they get away
from me.

02:24.633 --> 02:26.733
I'm gonna head up this ridge,
see what I can find up there.

02:32.467 --> 02:33.967
I'm getting up above
tree line now,

02:34.033 --> 02:37.300
I got to start
thinking about being quiet.

02:37.367 --> 02:39.667
I gotta start thinking about
the direction of the wind.

02:40.833 --> 02:41.967
How it's carrying my scent.

02:42.067 --> 02:44.300
And I got to start using
terrain to conceal myself,

02:45.067 --> 02:47.467
'cause the sheep are
very cautious animals.

02:54.633 --> 02:56.733
This is a sheep trail,
right here.

02:56.867 --> 02:58.100
There's sheep scat.

02:58.867 --> 03:01.433
There's a beautiful sheep
track right there.

03:01.533 --> 03:04.300
This is a path the sheep walk
regularly on this mountain.

03:07.633 --> 03:10.333
(SOFTLY) Scouting for sheep
is the same thing
as hunting 'em.

03:12.067 --> 03:14.400
The only difference is,
I'm not gonna shoot it
when I get there.

03:18.533 --> 03:21.133
But I'm trying
to stalk as close
as I can to any sheep.

03:21.233 --> 03:23.933
And anytime I'm out,
I'm gaining experience.

03:29.667 --> 03:33.933
These are all sheep beds
right here. This is where
sheep has laid its scat.

03:34.867 --> 03:36.533
There, here.

03:39.367 --> 03:43.300
This is more of a summer scat,
when they're eating
more succulent vegetation.

03:44.000 --> 03:47.433
In the winter,
it'll look more like this in
the wintertime.

03:49.067 --> 03:51.467
We're seeing lots
of sheep sign
on this mountain.

03:51.533 --> 03:54.600
So, I'm hopeful I might find
some sheep up here.

03:54.667 --> 03:55.967
Things are looking good.

04:02.433 --> 04:03.900
JESSIE HOLMES: To me,
living out in Alaska

04:03.967 --> 04:05.933
is all about
being able to take
care of yourself.

04:11.367 --> 04:13.833
Just got done having
my morning cup of coffee

04:13.900 --> 04:16.933
and down here I can see
the river really start
dropping last night.

04:17.933 --> 04:19.067
Dropped a couple feet.

04:19.933 --> 04:23.500
I'm gonna head upriver,
make sure my fish wheel
is not high and dry.

04:24.700 --> 04:25.967
I can't afford to just

04:26.033 --> 04:28.333
let a functionable fish wheel
go to waste, so...

04:28.433 --> 04:30.867
The water's been high
for about two weeks now,

04:30.967 --> 04:34.167
it just kind of like,
planed out
in the last couple of days,

04:34.233 --> 04:36.267
and just dropped overnight.
Just like that.

04:36.333 --> 04:38.767
And that's how this river is.
It's constantly changing.

04:43.833 --> 04:47.233
NARRATOR: Jessie Holmes
relies on the resources
along the Nenana River

04:47.300 --> 04:49.300
to maintain
a subsistence lifestyle.

04:50.733 --> 04:53.700
Getting his fish wheel
up and running is crucial
to feeding himself,

04:53.833 --> 04:56.300
and his team of sled dogs
for the year ahead.

05:02.433 --> 05:05.200
So, fish wheel is made out of
spruce log rafts

05:05.267 --> 05:07.033
and it floats out
in the river.

05:07.100 --> 05:09.400
What we do is,
we take it with big logs

05:09.467 --> 05:12.600
and push it far out
into the river,
into a deep channel.

05:12.667 --> 05:17.867
We drop the axel down,
and the big baskets
dip through the water.

05:17.933 --> 05:22.500
It's turning with the current,
as it scoops down,
the fish have no place to go,

05:22.567 --> 05:25.400
so they swim right
into the scoop.
Scoops 'em up.

05:25.467 --> 05:28.333
Now, the purpose of
a fish wheel is to put up
a large amount of fish.

05:29.367 --> 05:32.400
I can put up 900 fish
in a day,
if the fishing's going good.

05:33.367 --> 05:36.267
I need to be catching fish
and feeding the dogs fish
right now

05:36.333 --> 05:40.000
because it's the most
cost-effective way for me
to be able to keep these dogs.

05:42.900 --> 05:45.567
This could be a real big deal
to me to not be able to use
that fish wheel.

05:50.267 --> 05:52.600
My main goal
is to not fall in the river.

05:53.833 --> 05:58.033
It's one of the fastest
navigable waters in the U.S.,
the Tanana River is.

05:59.933 --> 06:01.833
And there's just tons of silt
in here.

06:02.367 --> 06:05.000
The minute you're in there,
the silt starts
filling your pockets,

06:05.067 --> 06:06.833
filling your clothes,
filling your boots.

06:06.900 --> 06:08.700
Little things can become
big things, quick.

06:14.367 --> 06:16.700
This thing's definitely
up on the sandbars.

06:17.900 --> 06:20.033
The river's dropped
a couple feet here.

06:21.400 --> 06:24.067
Yeah, it definitely looks like
I got my work ahead of me.

06:25.233 --> 06:28.733
If I don't get this thing
out here on
the water current soon,

06:28.800 --> 06:32.600
it's gonna get a lot worse,
'cause the river's
dropping fast.

06:32.733 --> 06:35.400
If I wait any longer on this,
it could put me
out of the season.

06:36.167 --> 06:38.233
It is stressful.
The stakes are high.

06:38.300 --> 06:41.100
And like,
it's very easy to mess up
with a fish wheel,

06:41.167 --> 06:42.467
there's a lot of things
going on.

06:42.567 --> 06:44.967
You got the current,
thousands of pounds,

06:45.033 --> 06:46.433
I mean,
this is gonna be
one hell of a job.

06:50.433 --> 06:52.667
Every minute that goes by
is a minute wasted,

06:52.767 --> 06:56.633
and another couple of inches
of water lost possibly,
so, it's time to get to work.

06:56.700 --> 06:59.767
Bust this thing out.
Get onto the next process.

06:59.833 --> 07:02.800
It's a lot of work,
but it provides a lot of food
for the dogs.

07:05.133 --> 07:06.633
There we go,
she's moving.

07:11.000 --> 07:14.300
SUE AIKENS: Your creativity,
your ingenuity,
and your ability to improvise.

07:14.767 --> 07:18.067
The mind is the most important
tool any of us carry around.

07:23.733 --> 07:25.667
Not feeling 100%.

07:25.833 --> 07:27.200
Just pushing it too hard.

07:27.267 --> 07:28.567
And it's showing.

07:28.633 --> 07:31.033
I'm exhausted,

07:31.100 --> 07:32.733
all of my stitches hurt.

07:34.000 --> 07:36.667
All of the things
I've been lifting,
pushing and pulling,

07:37.567 --> 07:40.367
the body is kicking my ass,
saying that I shouldn't.

07:44.100 --> 07:46.967
NARRATOR: Kavik River Camp
serves as a remote
fuelling station

07:47.033 --> 07:48.733
and bed and breakfast
for bush pilots.

07:50.100 --> 07:52.333
PILOT: Thank you.

07:52.400 --> 07:55.167
To sustain her business during
the busy summer months,

07:55.233 --> 07:57.533
Sue Aikens takes on
a heavy workload.

08:00.500 --> 08:02.267
AIKENS: (EXHALING) All right.

08:04.767 --> 08:08.733
NARRATOR: But an injury
has restricted her ability
to run Kavik on her own.

08:08.800 --> 08:10.933
And with clients
set to arrive soon,

08:11.033 --> 08:12.667
she must call for
reinforcements,

08:12.833 --> 08:15.000
or risk losing
crucial revenue.

08:17.967 --> 08:19.467
This is my windsock,

08:19.533 --> 08:20.867
and it's just
another one of those things

08:20.933 --> 08:23.233
that I can't do right now,
by myself.

08:25.367 --> 08:29.100
Part of being successful
is being brutally honest
with yourself.

08:29.167 --> 08:34.267
And to be brutally honest
with myself is to look at
my abilities and disabilities.

08:34.333 --> 08:36.433
Acknowledge them,
and work with them.

08:38.733 --> 08:41.200
It's summertime.
These tracks have to come off.

08:41.267 --> 08:43.900
These are 500 pounds
or so each.

08:43.967 --> 08:46.367
I do something this heavy
over my limits,

08:46.433 --> 08:47.933
and I'm gonna be
back in the hospital.

08:49.133 --> 08:52.533
There's just so many things
I can't do on my own.
I've got to get help.

09:00.000 --> 09:02.100
All right,
this is where I decide to

09:02.167 --> 09:04.800
throw up the white flag,
and go from tough to fluff.

09:06.333 --> 09:07.800
I'm gonna call my nephew,

09:08.800 --> 09:11.200
and see if he wants to come up
and help out his Auntie.

09:11.533 --> 09:15.700
There's way too much to do,
and I am incapable
of doing it right now.

09:18.600 --> 09:20.133
Hey, Jesse, how's it going?

09:20.200 --> 09:21.733
JESSE MOORE: I'm doing good,
how about you, Auntie?

09:21.867 --> 09:25.867
Um, well that's kind of
why I'm calling, uh...

09:26.000 --> 09:28.033
I'm trying to get everything
running up here,

09:28.133 --> 09:31.467
but there's just so much
stuff that I can't do.

09:31.567 --> 09:34.833
You wanna come help a gimpy
old woman out this summer?

09:35.267 --> 09:37.033
Yeah, that sounds perfect.

09:37.100 --> 09:39.233
Just let me know
when you want me
up there and I'll go.

09:39.333 --> 09:41.167
Can you be ready by tomorrow?

09:41.267 --> 09:44.433
Yeah, give me a couple hours
to pack up all my things,
and I should be up.

09:44.600 --> 09:46.500
All right, love you.
Thank you so much.

09:46.967 --> 09:48.767
-I love you too, Auntie.
-All righty, bye-bye.

09:50.100 --> 09:51.367
AIKENS: I have
a nephew, Jesse.

09:51.433 --> 09:53.700
He is one of
my brother's sons.

09:53.767 --> 09:55.567
He's a good young man.

09:55.633 --> 09:59.200
Maybe untried,
he's a little green
around the edges,

09:59.267 --> 10:01.267
when it comes to
remote camp life.

10:01.400 --> 10:03.467
He knows how to work
on machinery,

10:03.533 --> 10:05.000
but this is gonna be
a test for him.

10:08.900 --> 10:10.333
The world of Sue is tilting.

10:10.400 --> 10:13.167
People need this camp,
people need this service.

10:13.233 --> 10:15.033
It's an important dream
to keep alive,

10:15.100 --> 10:17.600
but I'm only gonna
keep it alive
if I bring on help.

10:20.867 --> 10:22.200
CHIP HAILSTONE: Some people
are about quantity.

10:22.267 --> 10:23.800
I'm about quality.

10:23.867 --> 10:26.133
I want quality food.
I don't want numbers.
I want results.

10:34.467 --> 10:37.533
AGNES HAILSTONE:
Jon and his oldest daughter
should be coming in soon.

10:37.933 --> 10:42.200
This is kind of exciting.
We haven't seen our grandbaby
since winter.

10:43.833 --> 10:47.667
NARRATOR: The Hailstone family
has a limited opportunity
to hunt for seals,

10:47.767 --> 10:50.167
a vital resource for
the long winter ahead.

10:51.733 --> 10:53.167
Seal hunting is
a native tradition

10:53.233 --> 10:55.367
that has been passed down
for generations.

10:56.833 --> 10:58.600
AGNES: Hi, Avery!

10:59.400 --> 11:01.367
You made it. (CHUCKLING)

11:04.733 --> 11:05.867
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

11:06.067 --> 11:08.433
AGNES: (KISSES)
I love you, Avery.

11:10.400 --> 11:13.100
CHIP: Jon's purpose here
is that he is an
excellent seal hunter.

11:13.200 --> 11:14.467
(GRUNTING)

11:15.633 --> 11:17.800
And, we have a very
brief time to go hunting.

11:17.867 --> 11:19.267
Usually, less than a week.

11:19.333 --> 11:20.667
Because pretty soon
this ice is gonna go out.

11:21.600 --> 11:23.433
Well, the importance
of getting the seals
right now,

11:23.500 --> 11:24.600
is that Ugruk that are here

11:24.667 --> 11:26.733
have migrated in
while the ice is apart,

11:26.800 --> 11:28.633
because they follow
the edge of the ice pack.

11:28.900 --> 11:31.100
And so,
when it's really solid,
they're not here.

11:31.233 --> 11:34.067
When it's starting to
break up, they come in,
they feed, they hang out,

11:34.167 --> 11:35.700
and when the ice goes,

11:35.767 --> 11:37.600
and follows
the end of the ice pack
as it recedes to the north,

11:37.667 --> 11:38.800
the Ugruk leave with it.

11:39.733 --> 11:41.133
They're only here for
a brief time.

11:42.433 --> 11:43.567
Usually less than a week.

11:44.667 --> 11:47.967
But when you do get one,
you get 900 pounds of meat
and blubber.

11:48.067 --> 11:50.067
And it's a huge factor
in the wintertime.

11:50.267 --> 11:52.133
And since winter's here
eight months of the year,

11:52.200 --> 11:53.700
seal oil's a pretty important
thing to have.

11:54.033 --> 11:55.867
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

11:55.933 --> 11:59.000
It's always good for one of
the boys to come in
and go hunt with me,

11:59.100 --> 12:03.067
because my husband's not able
to do the seal hunt with us,
'cause he's non-native.

12:03.133 --> 12:04.600
Hi, Avery.

12:09.333 --> 12:11.367
CHIP: We sit down
and we'll get the guns clean,

12:11.433 --> 12:13.500
and we'll get
everything sharpened.

12:13.567 --> 12:16.267
It's very important to get our
stuff sharpened.

12:16.333 --> 12:18.867
All our gear ready,
everything prepared,

12:18.933 --> 12:21.867
so that when we're out there,
there should be no mistakes.

12:21.933 --> 12:24.367
Everything we do now
is setting up for this hunt.

12:25.300 --> 12:26.900
(AGNES SPEAKING)

12:30.467 --> 12:33.133
I just want to make sure
it's nice and clean
and oiled up,

12:33.200 --> 12:34.800
because when salt water
go on it,

12:34.867 --> 12:37.033
it'll start to get
rusty real fast.

12:37.700 --> 12:39.133
CHIP: That's why these preps
are important.

12:39.200 --> 12:40.867
If we don't have
everything clean,

12:40.933 --> 12:42.600
all these hooks,
sharp and ready to use,

12:42.667 --> 12:46.167
just the first and only time
maybe this year,
it's not worth it.

12:47.267 --> 12:49.333
-(CLICKING)
-I think it's ready.

12:53.300 --> 12:56.867
CHIP: The three of us need
to know most importantly
is the way in and the way out.

12:56.967 --> 12:59.800
'Cause all that stuff
is only three feet deep,
and it freezes solid,

12:59.867 --> 13:01.233
and every year
it makes a new channel.

13:02.700 --> 13:05.033
Basically a river under water.

13:05.100 --> 13:07.067
And a lot of people have
no clue where that channel is.

13:07.167 --> 13:08.900
'Cause if you want
to go in that place,

13:08.967 --> 13:11.667
and you want to go
out of the lagoon down there,
you need to know.

13:11.733 --> 13:15.233
It's best if we all three go
together the first time,
and we go find the channel.

13:15.300 --> 13:17.567
And we go see where
it carves itself this year
after breakup.

13:17.633 --> 13:18.633
AGNES: Yeah.

13:20.400 --> 13:21.833
JON: Well, we've got
all of our gear ready.

13:22.600 --> 13:25.200
We're gonna go do
a little scout,
go look around.

13:25.267 --> 13:27.267
I gotta learn the channel,
it changes every year.

13:27.367 --> 13:29.533
We need this meat,
we need this oil.

13:29.600 --> 13:31.767
And once we get it,
we'll all be happy.

13:35.233 --> 13:37.867
AGNES: We're heading
down to the ocean.

13:38.967 --> 13:43.267
We're gonna go see
the ice conditions,
and go check out the channel.

13:43.367 --> 13:46.800
Just preparing for a hunt,
and if we're successful,

13:46.867 --> 13:49.733
then we should be able
to eat all winter long.

13:51.733 --> 13:54.367
We're at the mouth
of the Kiwalik River Lagoon,

13:54.433 --> 13:56.700
facing Kotzebue Sound ocean.

13:56.767 --> 13:58.767
And we're having a look here
at the ice,

13:58.833 --> 14:01.933
but the ice is at least
two or three miles away
and the wind is up.

14:02.000 --> 14:03.233
This is no day for us to hunt.

14:04.500 --> 14:08.467
When we try to go out hunting,
we usually wait
for the wind to stop blowing

14:08.600 --> 14:11.300
so that seals can
actually go on top the ice.

14:11.433 --> 14:13.033
(AGNES SPEAKING)

14:17.067 --> 14:18.900
Now that we figured out
the channel,

14:18.967 --> 14:20.967
and we figured out the tide,

14:21.033 --> 14:22.900
and we're out here scouting,

14:23.000 --> 14:25.967
we know what to expect
when we come back
the next time,

14:26.133 --> 14:28.133
so we're just gonna
head back to camp.

14:31.833 --> 14:33.300
CHIP: Whoa!
AGNES: What was that?

14:33.367 --> 14:34.467
I hit something.

14:34.533 --> 14:35.667
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)

14:35.800 --> 14:37.800
(CHIP SPEAKING)

14:40.533 --> 14:43.767
NARRATOR: The Hailstones
are surveying the waterways
to hunt for seal,

14:43.833 --> 14:46.000
a key resource for the family,

14:46.067 --> 14:48.033
but a stalled motor
has them dead in the water,

14:48.100 --> 14:49.733
and the tide is getting lower.

14:49.800 --> 14:51.033
(CHIP SPEAKING)

14:51.100 --> 14:52.233
JON: One, two, three.

14:52.300 --> 14:53.567
We broke our motor last year,

14:53.633 --> 14:55.800
and this was
the only replacement we got.

14:55.867 --> 14:57.733
And it's probably
gonna kill us.

14:58.767 --> 15:00.200
(CHIP SPEAKING)

15:00.267 --> 15:01.533
(JON SPEAKING)

15:04.767 --> 15:08.267
CHIP: Just the wrong
kind of motor and mount
for this kind of boat.

15:08.333 --> 15:11.833
Instead of the motor
being able to pop up,
it has a hydraulic lift,

15:11.900 --> 15:15.900
and it basically broke
the back of my transom
back here.

15:15.967 --> 15:17.733
I think I damaged my prop
a bit too,

15:17.800 --> 15:19.533
'cause I'm not getting
quite the push I was.

15:19.600 --> 15:22.933
We were trying to stay
in a channel that's
underwater in the lagoon.

15:23.000 --> 15:24.900
It's not always easy to do,

15:25.000 --> 15:26.467
it changes a little bit
every year,

15:27.200 --> 15:29.300
and I probably,
instead of making a curve,

15:29.400 --> 15:31.267
I probably cut it
a little bit on the inside,

15:31.333 --> 15:33.833
and I hit a stump
that's sitting out here.

15:34.567 --> 15:37.000
There's not much we can do to
repair it here and now,

15:37.067 --> 15:38.300
but we can repair it
back there.

15:41.633 --> 15:43.067
The water's about that deep

15:43.133 --> 15:44.700
and it's only
getting shallower

15:44.800 --> 15:48.067
'cause the tide is going down,
