I don't feel too terribly
well, right now.

16:50.367 --> 16:53.367
I am feeling mostly rundown.

16:53.433 --> 16:55.333
Honey is in here.
Powdered honey.

16:55.400 --> 16:58.333
But I got honey in there.
It's antibacterial,
antimicrobial.

16:58.800 --> 17:01.100
I'm gonna get fresh
water from the river.

17:01.467 --> 17:03.167
And then get the willow,
stuff it full,

17:03.267 --> 17:05.533
let all this stuff make out,
and, uh...

17:06.967 --> 17:08.967
See if I can't get myself
healthy from the inside out.

17:11.467 --> 17:14.667
NARRATOR: As Sue waits
for her nephew
to fly into Kavik,

17:14.767 --> 17:17.400
she battles the pain
from a recent injury

17:17.467 --> 17:18.900
by using a tundra remedy.

17:22.233 --> 17:25.500
AIKENS: I am not
a pup any more.
I'm a full-grown dog.

17:25.567 --> 17:29.633
My body parts hurt.
But my little sun tea here,
should be helping that.

17:29.700 --> 17:33.233
I'm gonna score up
a little bit of this,
so I can get the benefits,

17:33.433 --> 17:35.000
just kind of crush 'em up.

17:36.400 --> 17:38.400
And all this in here,
all that wetness,

17:38.467 --> 17:40.633
this plant has natural
salic acid.

17:41.867 --> 17:44.900
This right here,
is juvenile fireweed.

17:45.933 --> 17:48.433
So, toss a little bit of
that in there for some
added vitamin C.

17:52.600 --> 17:54.133
Nice, fresh river water.

17:54.400 --> 17:56.100
And I'll carry it back up.

17:56.167 --> 17:59.400
It's gonna take a while for it
to leech out its goodness,

17:59.500 --> 18:01.433
but, that's what
I'm hoping it does.

18:09.533 --> 18:10.667
(EXHALING)

18:10.733 --> 18:12.567
It's pretty tasty.
I just set it out.

18:12.633 --> 18:15.000
You know,
it's the fresh river water,

18:15.067 --> 18:17.767
it's not contaminated unless
you count fishy poop.

18:19.800 --> 18:21.300
I'm gonna take
a little bit of this,

18:22.067 --> 18:23.700
and go sit down,

18:23.767 --> 18:25.233
rest a little bit of that.

18:30.833 --> 18:32.733
VILLENEUVE: It isn't really
so important what you do,

18:32.800 --> 18:34.300
but it's important
how you feel about
what you do,

18:34.367 --> 18:36.100
and I feel good about
what I'm doing out here.

18:43.333 --> 18:47.433
Takes a lot of time and energy
and a lot of understanding of
their habits.

18:47.833 --> 18:50.833
That's why I'm out here
scouting now. To learn more.

18:51.000 --> 18:52.400
To see how the sheep
are doing,

18:52.467 --> 18:55.033
and to prepare myself for
hunting in a couple of months.

18:55.667 --> 18:57.833
NARRATOR: In order to hunt
Dall sheep in the fall,

18:57.900 --> 19:00.367
it's imperative for Glenn
to scout them now.

19:00.933 --> 19:04.267
But finding the illusive
animals in the steep
and deadly terrain,

19:04.333 --> 19:05.467
is a challenge.

19:08.267 --> 19:10.700
Every time I come up here
I discover new areas,

19:10.767 --> 19:12.567
new places
where sheep are hanging out.

19:13.833 --> 19:15.367
That's a big part of being
up here,

19:15.433 --> 19:16.933
just to learn more
about the animals.

19:18.400 --> 19:19.900
Get to know better
their behaviour,

19:19.967 --> 19:21.967
how they react
in different situations.

19:22.033 --> 19:24.900
Every time I go out
and spend time around sheep,
I learn something new.

19:27.067 --> 19:28.833
Look at this.

19:29.833 --> 19:31.333
A ram's horn.

19:32.900 --> 19:34.533
Sheep don't shed their horns.

19:34.600 --> 19:37.000
They're on for life.
That ram died
right around here.

19:37.067 --> 19:40.333
They've been here a long time,
but it shows that rams
are in this area.

19:40.800 --> 19:43.400
At least in the past,
there was a ram
right here at this lake.

19:43.467 --> 19:44.933
And that's where he died.

19:48.267 --> 19:50.300
The hunting regulations
only allow

19:50.367 --> 19:52.633
hunting of full-curl rams.

19:53.233 --> 19:56.567
The full-curl rams
tend to hang out
at steeper terrain.

19:57.467 --> 20:01.467
I've often found them
on steep rocks,
like cliffs, right here.

20:01.533 --> 20:03.733
They'll be up
on little ledges
on these cliffs.

20:03.833 --> 20:05.933
That's where I have to go
to find a full-curl ram.

20:09.467 --> 20:11.567
I wanna take a look over here.

20:11.700 --> 20:14.000
There! I see some
sheep right there.

20:16.833 --> 20:18.133
(SOFTLY)
There's a sheep trail,

20:18.200 --> 20:21.333
and right on the skyline,
a sheep was coming over it,

20:21.400 --> 20:23.300
and now there have been
eight sheep

20:23.367 --> 20:25.900
that have come into view,
following the same trail.

20:25.967 --> 20:27.800
Sheep will follow
the same trail for centuries.

20:29.133 --> 20:30.900
(VILLENEUVE SPEAKING)

20:50.933 --> 20:54.400
Right now, what I'm doing is
scouting around and just
looking for what areas

20:54.467 --> 20:57.933
are the most used by sheep
and where the sheep are
living up on this mountain.

20:58.000 --> 21:00.167
'Cause I wanna come back
in a couple of months
and hunt here.

21:00.233 --> 21:01.700
So, it's really
important to me.

21:01.767 --> 21:03.767
There are actually
a couple of sheep
just around this corner.

21:03.900 --> 21:06.600
I wanna try and sneak up
closer and see what I can see.

21:09.033 --> 21:10.433
Even when I'm scouting,
not hunting,

21:10.500 --> 21:12.167
it's really good practise
sneaking up on sheep,

21:12.233 --> 21:14.867
because they're so wary,
and they have such
keen senses.

21:15.667 --> 21:17.600
The more time I spend
around them,
the more I learn,

21:17.667 --> 21:19.333
the better my chances
are when I'm hunting.

21:19.433 --> 21:21.000
It's good to see
sheep this close.

21:29.667 --> 21:31.133
A little snow squall's
blowing through.

21:33.500 --> 21:35.767
You gotta be prepared
for any weather
this time of year.

21:35.900 --> 21:38.000
I never know what to expect
up in these mountains.

21:42.567 --> 21:43.667
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

21:49.967 --> 21:53.000
I'll get right up here on top,
pitch my tent,
spend the night right up here.

21:54.767 --> 21:56.533
The most dangerous thing
I do out here,

21:56.600 --> 21:58.400
is coming up in the mountains,
by myself.

21:58.467 --> 21:59.800
If I were to slip,
break a leg,

21:59.867 --> 22:01.133
or even just
twist an ankle badly,

22:01.200 --> 22:02.200
I wouldn't make it home.

22:06.033 --> 22:07.600
It's really blowing up here.

22:09.333 --> 22:11.300
I gotta find a place to camp,

22:11.367 --> 22:14.767
set up my tent
before this storm kicks up
even worse than this.

22:17.567 --> 22:19.433
Storms can blow in
fast like this,

22:19.500 --> 22:21.800
and won't necessarily
last too long,
but you never know.

22:23.667 --> 22:26.567
This time of year,
the weather could
just be about anything.

22:27.333 --> 22:28.400
(SIGHS)

22:31.933 --> 22:33.700
(SIGHS)

22:33.767 --> 22:36.733
Once I get my tent set up,
I'll be able to get
a little rest, then go out,

22:36.800 --> 22:38.500
look around on
the cliffs for sheep.

22:39.900 --> 22:42.467
Yeah, this is the place
to camp out,
right up above the sheep,

22:42.533 --> 22:43.833
then I have an advantage.

22:47.100 --> 22:49.933
One of my favourite ways
to stalk sheep is actually
to be up above 'em.

22:51.933 --> 22:53.433
When I get up on top of
the mountain,

22:53.500 --> 22:55.833
and they're
on the cliffs below me,
that's really ideal.

22:58.967 --> 23:02.767
It's good just to get in here,
out of the snow
and out of the wind.

23:02.833 --> 23:05.300
I'll just ride this snow storm
out in here.

23:06.267 --> 23:08.500
When the weather clears up,
I'll go back out,
looking for sheep.

23:15.100 --> 23:18.333
AIKENS: You prepare for
the worst and be pleasantly
surprised by the best.

