31:45.500 --> 31:48.333
Or the Ugruk aren't gonna
be able to go on it

31:48.400 --> 31:49.867
and rest on it.

31:49.967 --> 31:52.167
So what we're looking for is,

31:52.233 --> 31:57.100
a real big sheet of ice,
that can hold a lot of weight.

31:57.233 --> 32:00.400
So what we're gonna do is
we're gonna go
probably out more

32:00.467 --> 32:01.833
and go look for better ice.

32:07.167 --> 32:09.633
JON: This is one of
my absolute favourite times
to go hunt.

32:11.067 --> 32:13.567
It's beautiful weather.
It's a beautiful country.

32:14.400 --> 32:17.600
There's beautiful animals.
We've got all our guns ready.

32:18.367 --> 32:20.133
Get your hunt on and succeed.

32:20.200 --> 32:22.900
Once we have our food
set for the winter,
I'll be happy.

32:31.367 --> 32:32.367
(GUNSHOT)

32:40.667 --> 32:42.367
(JON SPEAKING)

32:58.267 --> 33:01.067
Go back to the boat,
try and see if I can sneak
on some other ones.

33:03.067 --> 33:06.200
Just gonna take it slow
and keep putting
around the edges

33:06.267 --> 33:09.833
and, hopefully,
we'll come across more seals
close to the edge of the ice.

33:18.833 --> 33:20.000
(AGNES SPEAKING)

33:27.700 --> 33:28.700
(GUNSHOT)

33:29.900 --> 33:31.867
AGNES: Too high!
JON: Way too high up.

33:31.933 --> 33:32.967
AGNES: Yeah.

33:39.767 --> 33:42.300
JON: I don't see any more
seals close by.

33:43.067 --> 33:45.633
AGNES: Doesn't look like
there's any seals
around this area.

33:45.700 --> 33:48.400
So we're slowly gonna
move our way back in.

33:48.467 --> 33:52.567
The tide is coming in
and the ice is starting
to go against the shore,

33:52.633 --> 33:56.867
so we just wanna make sure
we have our way
to get back into the channel

33:56.967 --> 33:58.600
to the mouth of the lagoon,

33:58.733 --> 34:01.300
before all the ice blocks us
and we can't make it.

34:02.333 --> 34:06.500
You really have to watch out
for ice you can't see
under the water

34:06.567 --> 34:10.200
because if you happen to go
and tip your boat over,
over an ice,

34:10.267 --> 34:13.067
it's cold water
and you'll just freeze
or die instantly.

34:14.300 --> 34:15.633
(JON SPEAKING)

34:25.700 --> 34:27.233
-We're in the channel?
-Yeah.

34:30.567 --> 34:32.067
AGNES: Lucky we learned
the channel, eh?

34:35.100 --> 34:36.533
(SPEAKING)

34:40.333 --> 34:41.333
(GUNSHOT)

34:42.633 --> 34:43.633
(EXCLAIMS)

34:48.467 --> 34:50.533
-All right.
-Hey, we got it.

34:50.600 --> 34:53.567
Right on, at least,
we got something in
the boat. Awesome.

34:54.567 --> 34:55.933
Perfect.

34:56.000 --> 34:57.567
Nice red-throated loon.

34:57.633 --> 35:00.133
Got past the shallows,
got a loon.

35:00.200 --> 35:02.667
Heading home. Right on.

35:04.067 --> 35:07.400
AGNES: We didn't get a seal
and we had quite
the experience

35:07.467 --> 35:08.833
and knew when to come back,

35:08.900 --> 35:10.167
and it just worked out
pretty good.

35:11.967 --> 35:13.200
AGNES:
It's always worth a try.

35:16.600 --> 35:17.967
Better luck next time.

35:18.033 --> 35:19.600
CHIP: Hopefully,
there will still be
another hunt.

35:19.700 --> 35:21.867
If not, in August,
the seals will be back.

35:26.100 --> 35:27.700
HOLMES: I love getting out
on the river,

35:27.767 --> 35:29.433
but this isn't
recreation to me.

35:29.500 --> 35:31.667
This is something
I just had to do
to maintain this lifestyle.

35:37.300 --> 35:38.567
(LEVER CREAKING)

35:41.067 --> 35:43.200
If I can just get this thing
out to some deeper water...

35:44.767 --> 35:46.600
I only moved it
quarter of an inch.

35:46.667 --> 35:50.533
I've seen the water drop at
least a couple inches,
so it's rapidly dropping.

35:50.600 --> 35:52.733
I have no choice.
I got to get this
thing off here now.

35:52.933 --> 35:55.333
If I mess around here,
this thing's gonna be
really stuck.

35:55.433 --> 35:56.500
I'm not gonna give up.

35:59.767 --> 36:02.000
NARRATOR: For Jessie
to harvest enough fish
to feed himself

36:02.067 --> 36:03.833
and his sled dogs
for the year,

36:03.900 --> 36:07.567
he must get his fish wheel
unstuck from the mud,
and back into the water.

36:08.033 --> 36:09.133
Starting to gain a little.

36:10.267 --> 36:12.800
It's a lot of physical labour
whenever you're doing
things on your own.

36:12.867 --> 36:14.533
Especially,
when you're working
with a fish wheel.

36:15.400 --> 36:19.633
Gonna go ahead and start
rigging a pulley up to this,
into some trees over here.

36:21.067 --> 36:23.067
My dogs gotta eat.
I gotta eat.

36:23.133 --> 36:24.467
I have to do these things.

36:24.700 --> 36:25.900
Especially,
when you're coming at it

36:25.967 --> 36:27.733
from a subsistence
lifestyle like I am,

36:27.800 --> 36:28.933
not a lot of money.

36:29.433 --> 36:31.967
I had to make up for that
in drive and determination.

36:32.033 --> 36:34.700
So when I start
a task like this,
I'm gonna finish it

36:34.767 --> 36:36.667
because that's what I'm gonna
do with every task I start.

36:37.600 --> 36:38.700
This is looking good.

36:38.833 --> 36:39.933
It's going pretty hard
at first,

36:40.000 --> 36:41.633
but getting it now.

36:42.500 --> 36:44.267
Still got a long way
to go, though.

36:50.800 --> 36:52.700
Oh, man.
This should have a pin here.

36:54.033 --> 36:55.400
The pin must have fell out.

36:57.900 --> 36:59.367
I don't have one here.

36:59.933 --> 37:02.933
So I'm just gonna use a nail.
See if that works.

37:04.867 --> 37:07.467
This is just
how it is out here,
you know?

37:07.533 --> 37:09.300
If something goes wrong,
you improvise.

37:11.600 --> 37:13.000
Find something else to use.

37:20.033 --> 37:21.500
All right, there it's going.

37:26.867 --> 37:27.867
Fuck! Man.

37:29.633 --> 37:31.200
Oh, the nail just broke.

37:33.067 --> 37:35.567
I'm gonna have to figure
something else out, for a pin.

37:35.633 --> 37:38.167
Those nails
aren't very strong.
Go over to the boat.

37:38.267 --> 37:40.700
I got some Allen wrenches
or something that could be
harder steel

37:40.767 --> 37:41.867
and hold for that.

37:47.067 --> 37:48.400
This should work a lot better.

37:48.467 --> 37:50.067
This is more harder
than steel.

37:54.667 --> 37:55.700
There we go.

38:02.333 --> 38:04.967
Just about to give this thing
a little bit of a push,

38:05.100 --> 38:07.400
and let the current start
building up against it.

38:09.367 --> 38:12.033
Glad to see it's not going
fast and that it's going slow.

38:12.100 --> 38:14.167
That's better, safer, thing.

38:14.367 --> 38:16.367
It's pretty shallow
right here, still.

38:18.900 --> 38:20.667
(CREAKING)

38:20.733 --> 38:21.933
Can't tell if it's moving.

38:22.933 --> 38:24.700
With a fish wheel

38:24.767 --> 38:27.233
there are so many dangers,
like, when you're rising it up
out of the water,

38:27.300 --> 38:29.233
you're rising 1,000
pounds out of the water,

38:29.300 --> 38:30.367
against the current.

38:30.433 --> 38:31.933
There's a lot of weight
sitting on this.

38:32.000 --> 38:34.067
If like, you aren't careful
with the way you do things,

38:34.133 --> 38:35.633
like this whole thing
could collapse.

38:35.700 --> 38:38.733
And I mean,
if that collapses on you,
in the river,

38:38.867 --> 38:41.633
against the current,
you wouldn't stand
much of a chance.

38:44.400 --> 38:46.167
My key thing is
to respect nature.

38:47.000 --> 38:50.500
Respect the river,
I want to work with the river,
not against it.

38:51.900 --> 38:53.233
Don't disrespect
Mother Nature,

38:53.300 --> 38:55.000
and, hopefully,
she's gonna take care of me.

38:55.067 --> 38:57.367
You never know
what's gonna happen,
you gotta be prepared.

39:09.467 --> 39:11.233
Yes! All right.

39:11.333 --> 39:14.600
Push it on out in
that current so it will break
up some of that stuff on it.

39:15.900 --> 39:17.033
There she goes.

39:18.867 --> 39:20.400
Get it up here.
That'd be perfect.

39:21.900 --> 39:25.333
I'm excited to, you know,
have this where it is now.

39:27.267 --> 39:29.133
I'm tired
and it's a good tired, though,

39:29.233 --> 39:31.167
you know, I like being tired
at the end of the day.

39:31.767 --> 39:33.533
Feel rest, you know, that way

39:33.600 --> 39:36.200
whenever I wake up
the next morning,
I feel really rested.

39:36.700 --> 39:38.900
It's like, take a lot of pride
in getting the job done,

39:38.967 --> 39:40.667
and keeping
a positive attitude.

39:42.600 --> 39:45.067
Now I just got to do
some minor repairs,

39:45.133 --> 39:47.200
get this thing
a little bit further upriver,

39:47.267 --> 39:50.500
and I feel good that I can
get this wheel running
and catching lots of fish.

39:50.567 --> 39:54.100
That's my goal.
So, I'm this much closer
to my fishing place.

40:00.033 --> 40:02.633
AIKENS: Remote people,
we have a vested interest,

40:02.733 --> 40:05.467
we put our backs into
our existence every
step of the way.

40:16.100 --> 40:17.300
JESSE: How heavy
are these tracks?

40:17.367 --> 40:19.033
Tracks are hundreds
of pounds each.

40:19.567 --> 40:21.100
But these tracks
have to come off.

40:22.200 --> 40:26.133
It's for winter only to add
traction and stability
when you're on snow and ice.

40:27.000 --> 40:29.767
But in the summer,
you got to have
the flexibility of the tyres.

40:33.200 --> 40:34.433
(DRILLING)

40:34.533 --> 40:37.233
I would say my mechanics skill
is above average.

40:37.300 --> 40:38.567
It's better than most, I mean,

40:39.100 --> 40:41.500
if anything has wheels
and a motor,
I can fix it, definitely.

40:41.567 --> 40:43.533
Or I can point out
the problem really fast.

40:51.900 --> 40:52.933
Good.

40:56.200 --> 40:58.700
The Bobcat tracks were
really heavy actually.

40:59.267 --> 41:01.867
I'm surprised that
she did 'em for
all those years by herself.

41:06.833 --> 41:07.867
There we go.

41:14.533 --> 41:16.133
Yeah, it's pretty crazy,
Auntie.

41:16.200 --> 41:17.667
It seems
like a two-person job.

41:18.300 --> 41:19.700
Not a one-person.

41:19.767 --> 41:22.767
-It's a one-person job
when it has to be.
-(CHUCKLING)

41:26.800 --> 41:28.833
AIKENS: The winter storms
were bad enough this year,

41:28.900 --> 41:32.967
that it took my old windsock
and blew it to kingdom come.

41:33.167 --> 41:38.333
This part will slip
over and down,
over that part, the very top.

41:40.067 --> 41:44.567
That sock will blossom out,
depending on what direction
the wind is coming from.

41:45.600 --> 41:48.800
Pilots can see from
a distance what direction
the wind's going,

41:48.867 --> 41:50.333
even if my radio
isn't working.

41:51.000 --> 41:52.700
So they can adjust
how they're gonna land.

41:53.733 --> 41:57.433
Really, no plausible way
for me to get up there
and do it.

41:57.500 --> 42:01.067
Typically, it takes two people

42:01.133 --> 42:02.800
and a running piece
of equipment.

42:06.200 --> 42:08.433
My nephew Jesse,
he's a sharp young man

42:08.500 --> 42:09.967
and knows
how to figure things out.

42:10.033 --> 42:11.633
And I can watch him
problem solve.

42:12.500 --> 42:13.833
It's like watching your babies

42:13.900 --> 42:15.533
when they first
learn to crawl.

42:15.600 --> 42:16.833
And that's what I want to see.

42:16.900 --> 42:19.300
It takes
a problem-solver out here.

42:21.100 --> 42:22.733
AIKENS: I'm gonna have you
take me up,

42:22.800 --> 42:24.967
just a few feet,
and then level it out.

42:25.567 --> 42:27.333
Okay, stop. This way.

42:32.900 --> 42:34.033
Hold it there.

42:37.133 --> 42:39.367
My nephew Jesse ended up
taking me up on my offer.

42:40.333 --> 42:41.333
Hold it still.

42:45.800 --> 42:47.800
I had to admit I hit the wall.

42:47.867 --> 42:51.533
I'm not able to do the chores
that I should be able to do,
that I used to be able to do.

42:51.600 --> 42:55.733
And if I try to,
even want to keep Kavik open,
I have to get help.

42:58.800 --> 43:01.400
Well, you did a good job.
I appreciate it.

43:01.467 --> 43:03.467
-AIKENS: You big lug.
-(JESSE LAUGHING)

43:04.667 --> 43:08.700
If I don't stay in the black,
Suzy doesn't come back.

43:11.467 --> 43:12.800
(FLAPPING)
